Q11. Difference between == and === in JavaScript?
---------------------------------------------------
Operator	Name	Checks
==	Loose equality	Value only
===	Strict equality	Value + Type
== Example
console.log(5 == "5");
Output
true
Because type conversion happens.
=== Example
console.log(5 === "5");
Output
false
Because:
Number ≠ String
✅ Simple Rule
==   → checks value
===  → checks value + datatype
Most developers prefer ===.

Q12. What are the types of functions in JavaScript? What are named and anonymous functions?
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
JavaScript has different types of functions.
Common types of functions
Named Function
Anonymous Function
Function Expression
Arrow Function
Callback Function
Higher-order Function
Named Function
A named function has a function name.
Example
function greet() {
  console.log("Hello Mahesh");
}
greet();
Output
Hello Mahesh
Here greet is the function name.
Anonymous Function
An anonymous function does not have a name.
Usually used inside variables or callbacks.
Example
let sayHello = function() {
  console.log("Hello");
};
sayHello();
Here the function has no name.
Q13. What is Function Expression in JavaScript?
------------------------------------------------
A function expression means storing a function inside a variable.
Example
let add = function(a, b) {
  return a + b;
};
console.log(add(5,3));
Output
8
Here the function is assigned to variable add.
Q14. What are Arrow Functions in JavaScript?
---------------------------------------------
Arrow functions are a short and modern way to write functions.
They use the => arrow symbol.
Normal Function
function add(a,b){
  return a + b;
}
Arrow Function
const add = (a,b) => {
  return a + b;
};
console.log(add(5,3));
Output
8
Short Arrow Function
const add = (a,b) => a + b;
Q15. What are Callback Functions?
---------------------------------
A callback function is a function passed as an argument to another function.
It is called later by another function.
Example
function greet(name, callback){
  console.log("Hello " + name);
  callback();
}
function sayBye(){
  console.log("Goodbye");
}
greet("Mahesh", sayBye);
Output
Hello Mahesh
Goodbye
Here sayBye is the callback function.
Q16. When to use Callback Functions in real applications?
--------------------------------------------------------------
Callbacks are used when a task takes time and we want to run another function after it finishes.
Real Examples
1️⃣ API calls
fetch("data.json", function(data){
   console.log(data);
});
2️⃣ Button click events
button.addEventListener("click", function(){
  console.log("Button clicked");
});
3️⃣ Timer functions
setTimeout(function(){
  console.log("Hello after 2 seconds");
}, 2000);
