Q18. What is a Higher-order Function?
--------------------------------------
A higher-order function is a function that:
1️⃣ Takes another function as an argument
OR
2️⃣ Returns a function
Example
function greet(name){
  return function(){
    console.log("Hello " + name);
  };
}
let sayHello = greet("Mahesh");
sayHello();
Output
Hello Mahesh
Another Example (Array method)
let numbers = [1,2,3];
numbers.forEach(function(num){
  console.log(num);
});
Here forEach is a higher-order function because it accepts a function.

Q19. What are Asynchronous Operations in JavaScript?
-----------------------------------------------------
Asynchronous operations are tasks that run in the background without stopping the rest of the program.
JavaScript does not wait for the task to finish and continues executing other code.
Example
Tasks like:
API calls
File loading
Database requests
Timers
Example Code
console.log("Start");
setTimeout(function(){
  console.log("This runs after 2 seconds");
}, 2000);
console.log("End");
Output
Start
End
This runs after 2 seconds
JavaScript does not wait for setTimeout.
Q20. What are Promises in JavaScript?
--------------------------------------------
A Promise is an object that represents the result of an asynchronous operation.
It tells whether the operation is:
1️⃣ Pending – still running
2️⃣ Resolved (Fulfilled) – completed successfully
3️⃣ Rejected – operation failed
Promise Example
let promise = new Promise(function(resolve, reject){
    let success = true;
    if(success){
        resolve("Task completed");
    }else{
        reject("Task failed");
    }
});
Q21. How to implement Promises in JavaScript?
----------------------------------------------
Promises are handled using:
.then()
.catch()
.finally()
Example
let promise = new Promise(function(resolve, reject){
    resolve("Data received");
});
promise
.then(function(result){
    console.log(result);
})
.catch(function(error){
    console.log(error);
});
Output
Data received
Example with reject
let promise = new Promise(function(resolve, reject){
    reject("Error occurred");
});
promise
.then(function(result){
    console.log(result);
})
.catch(function(error){
    console.log(error);
});
Output
Error occurred
Q22. When to use Promises in real applications?
------------------------------------------------
Promises are used when handling asynchronous tasks.
Common real examples
1️⃣ API calls
fetch("https://api.example.com/data")
.then(response => response.json())
.then(data => console.log(data))
.catch(error => console.log(error));
2️⃣ Database requests
3️⃣ File uploads
4️⃣ Authentication requests
Promises help avoid callback hell.
Q23. What are Classes and Objects in JavaScript?
-------------------------------------------------
Object
An object stores data and behavior together.
Example
let person = {
  name: "Mahesh",
  age: 25
};
console.log(person.name);
Output
Mahesh
Class
A class is a blueprint used to create objects.
Example
class Person {
  constructor(name, age){
    this.name = name;
    this.age = age;
  }
}
let p1 = new Person("Mahesh",25);
console.log(p1.name);
